Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot of salted
water to a boil. Thinly slice @scallions{4}(thinly sliced, keeping greens and whites
separate). Toss @cauliflower florets{20%oz} on a #baking sheet{} with a large
drizzle of @olive oil{4%tsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast until golden
brown and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Boil the cavatappi: Add @cavatappi pasta{12%oz} to boiling water. Cook until al
dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain.

Meanwhile, heat a large #pan over medium-high heat. Add @pancetta{4%oz} and
scallion whites, and toss until crispy, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from pan, retaining
as much oil as possible.

Heat @butter{2%tbsp} in same pan over medium heat. Once melted, whisk in
@flour{2%tbsp}. Whisk constantly ~{1-2%minutes}. Very slowly whisk in
@milk{2%box} until combined. Add @chicken stock concentrate{2} and simmer until
thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove pan from heat, then stir in
@Italian cheese blend{1%cup}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir cavatappi, pancetta mixture, and ¾ of the cauliflower into cheese sauce.
Transfer to a large, lightly oiled #baking dish{}. Top with remaining cauliflower,
and cook until bubbling, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Serve: Garnish with scallion greens and enjoy!

> If your pan is ovenproof, you can skip transferring to a separate baking dish.